IFC Lends $215 Million for Jordan-India Fertilizer Venture

-- B y   N a y l a   R a z z o u k
-- 
2011-06-08T10:48:32Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-08/ifc-lends-215-million-for-jordan-india-fertilizer-venture.html
The International Finance Corp., a
part of the World Bank, is lending  Jordan India Fertilizer Co. 
$215 million to build a phosphoric acid plant in Jordan,
according to a statement on the IFC  website .  The plant, for which the  European Investment Bank  is
providing another $120 million, will have a production capacity
of 1,500 tons a day.  Jordan India Fertilizer is a joint venture between Indian
Farmers Fertilizer Cooperative Ltd., which has 52 percent, and
 Jordan Phosphate Mines (JOPH)  Co., the worldâ€™s second-biggest exporter
of phosphate rock, with 48 percent.  To contact the reporters on this story: Nayla Razzouk in Amman
